=== Pre-California statehood ===
The valley was a center of "the crossroads of cultures and languages, including the [[Tongva|Tongva]], [[Fernandeno|Fernandeño]], and [[Chumash_people|Chumash]]."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/projects/la-me-tongva-map/|title=Mapping the Tongva villages of L.A.'s past|last1=Greene|first1=Sean|last2=Curwen|first2=Thomas|date=9 May 2019|newspaper=LA Times|access-date=19 June 2019|archive-date=2020-12-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201228031020/https://www.latimes.com/projects/la-me-tongva-map/|dead-url=no}}</ref> The Tongva, later known as the [[Gabrieleño|Gabrieleño]] [[Mission_Indians|Mission Indians]] after colonization, the [[Tataviam_people|Tataviam]] to the north, and Chumash to the west, had lived and thrived in the valley and its arroyos for over 8,000 years.<ref name=prehistoric>{{cite web| title=Prehistoric milling site found in California| url=https://www.usatoday.com/tech/science/discoveries/2006-03-03-prehistoric-mill_x.htm| work=[[USA_Today|USA Today]]| date=March 4, 2006| access-date=August 8, 2012| archive-date=2011-05-23| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523072240/http://www.usatoday.com/tech/science/discoveries/2006-03-03-prehistoric-mill_x.htm| dead-url=no}}</ref> They had [[:Category:Former_Native_American_populated_places_in_California|numerous settlements]], and trading and hunting camps, before the [[Spanish_colonization_of_the_Americas|Spanish]] arrived in 1769 to settle in the Valley.<ref name="Klein2003">{{cite book| author=Jake Klein| title=Then & Now: San Fernando Valley| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=04NDcqx9fNYC| access-date=8 August 2012| date=1 June 2003| publisher=Gibbs Smith| isbn=978-1-58685-229-0| page=5| archive-date=2020-12-16| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201216060420/https://books.google.com/books?id=04NDcqx9fNYC| dead-url=no}}</ref>
[[File:Eulogio_de_Celis.jpg|缩略图]] ranchero [[Eulogio_F._de_Celis|Eulogio F. de Celis]] once owned most of the San Fernando Valley.]]
The first [[Ranchos_of_California#Spanish_era|Spanish land grant]] in the San Fernando Valley (or ''El Valle de Santa Catalina de Bononia de los Encinos''<ref name="Crosby2009">{{cite book| author=Michael Crosby| title=Encino| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YTfgQM9pOcAC&pg=PA7| access-date=8 August 2012| date=3 June 2009| publisher=Arcadia Publishing| isbn=978-0-7385-6991-8| page=7| archive-date=2021-01-17| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117112320/https://books.google.com/books?id=YTfgQM9pOcAC&pg=PA7| dead-url=no}}</ref>) was called "Rancho Encino" (present-day [[Mission_Hills,_Los_Angeles|Mission Hills]] on the ''Camino Viejo'' before [[Newhall_Pass|Newhall Pass]]), in the northern part of the San Fernando Valley. [[Juan_Francisco_Reyes_(soldier)|Juan Francisco Reyes]] built an [[adobe|adobe]] dwelling beside a [[:Category:Tongva_settlements|Tongva village]] or [[rancheria|rancheria]] at [[Spring_(hydrology)|natural springs]], but the land was soon taken from him so that a [[Spanish_missions_in_California|mission]] could be built there.<ref name="California">{{cite book| author=Historic Spots in California| title=Historic Spots in California: The Southern Counties| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EXGaAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA59| access-date=8 August 2012| publisher=Stanford University Press| isbn=978-0-8047-1614-7| page=59| archive-date=2020-10-02| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201002010030/https://books.google.com/books?id=EXGaAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA59| dead-url=no}}</ref> [[Mission_San_Fernando_Rey_de_España|Mission San Fernando Rey de España]] was established in 1797 as the 17th of the 21 missions.<ref name="VI">{{cite book| author1=California Mission Series| author2=Vol VI| title=California Mission Series, Vol VI: Mission San Miguel, Mission San Fernando Rey, Mission San Luis Rey| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xXSaAAAAIAAJ&pg=PT40| access-date=8 August 2012| publisher=Stanford University Press| isbn=978-0-8047-1875-2| page=40| archive-date=2020-08-20| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200820023919/https://books.google.com/books?id=xXSaAAAAIAAJ&pg=PT40| dead-url=no}}</ref> The land trade granted Juan Francisco Reyes the similarly named [[Rancho_Los_Encinos|Rancho Los Encinos]], also beside springs ([[Los_Encinos_State_Historic_Park|Los Encinos State Historic Park]] in present-day [[Encino,_Los_Angeles|Encino]]). Later the [[Ranchos_of_California#Mexican_era|Mexican land grant]]s of [[Rancho_El_Escorpión|Rancho El Escorpión]] ([[West_Hills,_Los_Angeles|West Hills]]), [[Rancho_Providencia|Rancho Providencia]] and [[Rancho_Cahuenga|Rancho Cahuenga]] ([[Burbank,_California|Burbank]]), and [[Rancho_Ex-Mission_San_Fernando|Rancho Ex-Mission San Fernando]] (rest of valley) covered the San Fernando Valley.{{citation needed|date= November 2014}}

The [[Treaty_of_Cahuenga|Treaty of Cahuenga]], ending the [[Mexican–American_War|Mexican–American War]] fighting in [[Alta_California|Alta California]], was signed in 1847 by [[Californio|Californio]]s and Americans at [[Campo_de_Cahuenga|Campo de Cahuenga]], the Verdugo Family adobe at the entrance to the [[Cahuenga_Pass|Cahuenga Pass]] in the southeast San Fernando Valley ([[North_Hollywood,_Los_Angeles|North Hollywood]]). The 1848 [[Treaty_of_Guadalupe_Hidalgo|Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo]] ended the entire war.

=== California statehood and beyond ===
The Valley officially became part of the State of California on September 9, 1850, when the [[California_Statehood_Act|California Statehood Act]] was approved by the federal government.
In 1874, [[Dryland_farming|dry wheat farming]] was introduced by [[James_Boon_Lankershim|J. B. Lankershim]] and [[Isaac_Newton_Van_Nuys|Isaac Van Nuys]], which became very productive for their San Fernando Homestead Association that owned the southern half of the valley. In 1876, they sent the first wheat shipment from both [[San_Pedro,_Los_Angeles|San Pedro]] Harbor and from the United States to Europe.<ref name="MayersMassaro1976">{{cite book| author1=Jackson Mayers| author2=Nick Massaro| title=The San Fernando Valley| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UAcSAQAAIAAJ| access-date=6 May 2013| year=1976| publisher=John D. McIntyre| page=67| archive-date=2020-12-16| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201216060418/https://books.google.com/books?id=UAcSAQAAIAAJ| dead-url=no}}</ref>

