== 教育 ==
{{transh}}
Public schools in the San Fernando Valley are served by three unified school districts; The Northwest and East Regions of the [[Los_Angeles_Unified_School_District|Los Angeles Unified School District]], the [[Glendale_Unified_School_District|Glendale Unified School District]] and the [[Burbank_Unified_School_District|Burbank Unified School District]]. There are four community colleges in the valley; [[Los_Angeles_Valley_College|Los Angeles Valley College]] in Valley Glen, [[Los_Angeles_Mission_College|Los Angeles Mission College]] in Sylmar, and [[Los_Angeles_Pierce_College|Los Angeles Pierce College]] in Woodland Hills. All except Glendale College are served by the [[Los_Angeles_Community_College_District|Los Angeles Community College District]]. The only state university in the San Fernando Valley is [[California_State_University_Northridge|California State University Northridge]] in Northridge.

In 1994 there were 180,000 PK-12 students attending [[Los_Angeles_Unified_School_District|Los Angeles Unified School District]] (LAUSD) campuses in the Valley. During the same year, about 45,000 PK-12 students, or one in five of all such students, attended the over 200 private schools in the Valley.<ref>"[https://articles.latimes.com/1994-11-30/local/me-3217_1_private-schools Choosing A Campus : A Guide To the Largest Private Schools in the Valley] {{Wayback|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1994-11-30/local/me-3217_1_private-schools |date=20170525062147 }}." ''[[Los_Angeles_Times|Los Angeles Times]]''. November 30, 1994. Valley Briefing. Retrieved on March 23, 2014.</ref>

