=== Independence movements ===
The Valley attempted to secede in the 1970s, but the state passed a law barring city formation without the approval of the City Council. In 1997, Assemblymen [[Robert_Hertzberg|Bob Hertzberg]] and [[Tom_McClintock|Tom McClintock]] helped pass a bill that would make it easier for the Valley to secede by removing the City Council veto. AB 62 was signed into law by Governor [[Pete_Wilson|Pete Wilson]]. Meanwhile, a grassroots movement to split the [[Los_Angeles_Unified_School_District|Los Angeles Unified School District]] (LAUSD) and create new San Fernando Valley-based school districts became the focal point of the desire to leave the city. Though the state rejected the idea of Valley-based districts, it remained an important rallying point for Hertzberg's mayoral campaign, which proved unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/29/us/los-angeles-long-fragmented-faces-threat-of-secession-by-the-sanfernando-valley.html |title=Los Angeles, Long Fragmented, Faces Threat of Secession by the San Fernando Valley |newspaper=[[The_New_York_Times|The New York Times]] |first=B. Drummond |last=Ayres Jr. |date=May 29, 1996 |access-date=1 October 2016 |archive-date=2017-09-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901160533/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/29/us/los-angeles-long-fragmented-faces-threat-of-secession-by-the-sanfernando-valley.html |dead-url=no }}</ref>

;Measure F

In 2002, the San Fernando Valley portion of Los Angeles again seriously campaigned to [[secession|secede]] from the rest of the city and become its own new independent and incorporated city. The movement gained some momentum, but measure F did not receive the necessary votes to pass. There were multiple name choices for the new city. "Valley City" was the chosen name for the new city. Among the proposed names for the new city were "Mission Valley", "Rancho San Fernando", "Camelot", or "Townsville".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pdf.oac.cdlib.org/pdf/cnos/urba/csun_urb_vote_oac.pdf |title=Guide to the Valley Voters Organized Toward Empowerment Collection |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2012 |publisher=Online Archive of California |access-date=September 17, 2020 |archive-date=2021-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211128060307/http://pdf.oac.cdlib.org/pdf/cnos/urba/csun_urb_vote_oac.pdf |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kahn |first=Joseph |date=April 20, 2002 |title=San Fernando Valley Looks To a Life After Los Angeles |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/20/us/san-fernando-valley-looks-to-a-life-after-los-angeles.html |work=[[The_New_York_Times|The New York Times]] |access-date=September 17, 2020 |archive-date=2022-01-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120140818/https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/20/us/san-fernando-valley-looks-to-a-life-after-los-angeles.html |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sauerwein |first=Kristina |date=March 18, 2003 |title=Champion of Valley Secession Passes Control to New Leader |work=Los Angeles Times }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=It's Right on the Tip of Their Tongues; Secession: Residents of Valley and harbor area narrow list of possible names |work=Los Angeles Times |date=April 3, 2002 }}</ref>

