== 地产价值 ==
{{transh}}
In 1997, the [[median|median]] price of an average one-family home in the San Fernando Valley was only $155,000. In the summer of 2003, it reached $400,000 and by July 2005, it had reached $578,500. In August 2005, it rose to $600,000. A cooling off was noted in 2006, when between November 2005 and November 2006, median prices rose by the smallest amount of any 12-month period since mid-1997. Indeed, November prices were lower than October prices, and sales for November had fallen 19.1% compared to a year earlier.<ref>{{cite web| title=SFV Economy watch| url=http://www.csun.edu/sfverc/| work=San Fernando Valley Economic Research Center| publisher=[[California_State_University,_Northridge|California State University, Northridge]]| access-date=2022-02-27| archive-date=2012-12-04| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204235530/http://www.csun.edu/sfverc/| dead-url=no}}</ref> The [[United_States_housing_market_correction|United States housing market correction]] affected the San Fernando Valley in 2007–2009, making housing significantly more affordable in the area: the median sales price fell from $660,000 at the peak in May 2007, to $500,000 by March 2008,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csun.edu/sfverc/reports/pdfs/08/CSUN_SFV_Economic_Report_08.pdf |title= The CSUN San Fernando Valley Economic Report | date = 2008 |access-date=2008-07-07 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080910174331/http://www.csun.edu/sfverc/reports/pdfs/08/CSUN_SFV_Economic_Report_08.pdf |archive-date=2008-09-10 }}</ref> stabilizing in 2009 at around $330,000–$340,000.<ref>[http://www.dqnews.com/Charts/Annual-Charts/CA-City-Charts/ZIPCAR09.aspx California Home Sale Activity by City Chart] {{Wayback|url=http://www.dqnews.com/Charts/Annual-Charts/CA-City-Charts/ZIPCAR09.aspx |date=20120111130820 }}. DQNews. Retrieved on 2010-12-07.</ref> The San Fernando Valley is home to one of the most expensive housing markets in the country. The median home value as of July 2014 is $536,000, the highest in the region in 8 years.<ref>{{cite web| title=Valley Home Prices Hit Eight Year High| url=http://www.sfvbj.com/news/2014/jul/25/valley-home-prices-hit-eight-year-high| work=San Fernando Valley Blog Journal| publisher=San Fernando Valley Blog Journal| access-date=13 October 2017| archive-date=2014-07-27| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727193237/http://www.sfvbj.com/news/2014/jul/25/valley-home-prices-hit-eight-year-high/| dead-url=no}}</ref> As of 2017, the price of an average single family house in the San Fernando Valley was over $800,000, making the valley one of the most expensive places to live in the [[Los_Angeles_metropolitan_area|Los Angeles metropolitan area]].


